    "reflection": "Moses tells Israel to remember both its hunger and God's faithful provision in the desert. The manna taught the people that life depends on what comes from God, not merely on what they can secure for themselves. Jesus brings that lesson to fulfillment by giving his own flesh and blood as true food and drink. The Eucharist is not only private nourishment; Paul says that sharing the one loaf makes the many into one body. Receiving Christ therefore joins worship, dependence, and communion. We approach the altar admitting that we cannot give ourselves eternal life and cannot live Christian discipleship by willpower alone. At the same time, receiving one Lord commits us to live as one body, especially when preference, resentment, or social difference would divide us. Corpus Christi asks whether Eucharistic belief is shaping our ordinary lives: our gratitude, our treatment of fellow parishioners, our willingness to reconcile, and our readiness to become nourishment for others through sacrificial love.",
