    "reflection": "Isaiah compares God's word to rain that makes the earth fertile and accomplishes its purpose. Jesus focuses on the receiving soil. The same seed encounters a hard path, shallow rock, choking thorns, and rich ground. The parable moves the question away from whether God's word is effective and toward what is happening within the hearer. A hardened heart may refuse understanding; enthusiasm without roots collapses under pressure; anxiety and the lure of riches can slowly crowd out what was received. Rich soil is not passive. It hears, understands, perseveres, and bears fruit. Paul places this growth within a wider hope: creation groans as it awaits redemption. Our struggles do not mean that God has stopped working, but growth often requires patient cultivation. These readings invite us to name what currently steals, scorches, or chokes the word in us. They also remind us that small practices of attention, prayer, obedience, and endurance prepare soil in which God's word can accomplish more than immediate emotion ever could.",
