    "reflection": "Wisdom describes God's power as the source of justice and, surprisingly, of leniency. Because God is truly sovereign, he does not need to react with insecurity or haste. Jesus' parables show that same patience. Wheat and weeds grow together for a time because premature uprooting could damage what is good. Mustard seed and yeast work quietly before their full effect becomes visible. This patience is not indifference to evil; the Gospel still promises a final judgment and separation. It is mercy that leaves room for repentance and protects developing good. The Spirit also meets us in weakness, interceding when we cannot even find the right words to pray. These readings challenge both harsh judgment and passive avoidance. We are called to name evil truthfully while resisting the urge to reduce people to their worst moment. In ourselves, our families, and our communities, God's work may be real before it is impressive. Faithful disciples learn to correct with kindness, pray through uncertainty, and trust God with growth they cannot force.",
